The `drawCube` function sets up OpenGL uniforms by binding the pipeline, setting the projection matrix with `glUniformMatrix4fv`, setting the view matrix with `glUniformMatrix4fv`, and setting the model position, lower bounds, upper bounds, and line size using `glUniform3f` and `glUniform1f`. The relevant code is as follows:

```zig
pipeline.bind(null);
c.glUniformMatrix4fv(uniforms.projectionMatrix, 1, c.GL_TRUE, @ptrCast(&projectionMatrix));
c.glUniformMatrix4fv(uniforms.viewMatrix, 1, c.GL_TRUE, @ptrCast(&viewMatrix));
c.glUniform3f(
    uniforms.modelPosition,
    @floatCast(relativePositionToPlayer[0]),
    @floatCast(relativePositionToPlayer[1]),
    @floatCast(relativePositionToPlayer[2]),
);
c.glUniform3f(uniforms.lowerBounds, min[0], min[1], min[2]);
c.glUniform3f(uniforms.upperBounds, max[0], max[1], max[2]);
c.glUniform1f(uniforms.lineSize, 1.0/128.0);
```

The `swizzle` function rearranges the components of a vector. It takes a vector `v` and four compile-time constants representing the new order of components. The function uses Zig's `@shuffle` intrinsic to create a new vector with the specified component order. Here is the code example:

```zig
pub inline fn swizzle(
    v: Vec4f,
    comptime x: Vec4fComponent,
    comptime y: Vec4fComponent,
    comptime z: Vec4fComponent,
    comptime w: Vec4fComponent,
) Vec4f {
    return @shuffle(f32, v, undefined, [4]i32{@intFromEnum(x), @intFromEnum(y), @intFromEnum(z), @intFromEnum(w)});
}
```

